AllLife Bank - Personal Loan Campaign¶

Loan Modeling¶

Background and Context¶

AllLife Bank is a US bank with a growing customer base. The majority of these customers are liability customers (depositors). The number of customers who are also borrowers (asset customers) is quite small, and the bank is looking at expanding this base rapidly to bring in more loan business and earn more through the interest. Management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors).

A campaign run last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio.

My Objective¶

As a Data Scientist for AllLife Bank I am going to use Exploratory Data Analysis, Logistic Regression models, Decision Tree models, and model tuning methods to find out which variables in the dataset are most significant at predicting whether or not a customer will purchase a personal loan. I will then use my findings, from these models, to make my reccomendations to the marketing department as to which customer segment should be targeted.

Data Dictionary¶

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Customer’s age in completed years
  • Experience: #years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousand dollars)
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
  • Family: the Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)
  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate; 3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (in thousand dollars)
  • Personal_Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign?
  • Securities_Account: Does the customer have a securities account with the bank?
  • CD_Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank?
  • Online: Do customers use internet banking facilities?
  • CreditCard: Does the customer use a credit card issued by any other Bank (excluding All life Bank)?

# creating a code to create a histogram and boxplot for each of our variables
def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12,7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Creating a histogram and boxplot

    data: dataframe
    feature: loan[column]
    figsize: size of figure
    kde: show density curve (default: False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default: None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # rows of subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # subplots share x-axis
        gridspec_kw={'height_ratios': (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    ) # create subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=loan, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color='yellow'
    ) # boxplot will have a green triangle representing the mean
    sns.histplot(
        data=loan, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, pallete='winter'
    )   if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color='red', linestyle='--'
    ) # Add mean line to histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color='black', linestyle='-'
    ) # Add median line to histogram

  • It looks like we have 33 customers showing -1 years of Experience, 15 with -2 years, and 4 with -3 years.
  • There are 2 possible explanations here. 1. The data was entered correctly for the number of years, but with a negative sign by mistake, so all these customers have 1, 2, or 3 years of experience, respectively, and we can just remove the negative sign. 2. It is probably safer to assume they were just data collection/entry errors altogether and replace them with missing values and then impute them with the mean in this case as it is a fairly normal distribution and the mean and median are both 20 years Experience in this case.
  • In this case I think it is safer to assume it was incorrect data and replace the values as missing and then impute them.

Bivariate Analysis¶

In [42]:
def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: loan
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = loan[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = loan[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(loan[predictor], loan[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False  
    )
    print(tab1)
    print('-' * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(loan[predictor], loan[target], normalize='index').sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, figsize=(count + 5, 6))
    plt.legend(
        loc='lower left', frameon=False
    )
    plt.legend(loc='upper left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

Summary of EDA¶

  • Based on the EDA you want to look at customers over the age of 25, as customers who are 23, 24, and 25 years old did not accept any personal loans.
  • You would also want to look at customers making over 60,000 a year as no one making less than that accepted a personal loan.
  • Education shows that customers who have an advanced/Professional level of education have the highest number of customers who accepted personal loans.
  • You may also want to look at customers with 3 person families as that was the highest family category amongst customers accepting personal loans.
  • One factore that seems like it may have a stronger influence is whether or not a customer has a CD Account with the bank, as there was a 50% acceptance rate of personal loans for those customers having a CD Account.
  • Certain counties may have an influence such as Sonoma County or Shasta County as they had higher acceptance rates, but overall, the actual number of customers with personal loans from those counties were not large amounts.
  • So as of right now, just based on EDA, the customers to focues on would be those over 25, with a 3 person family, having an advanced/professional education, earning more than 60,000 per yer year, who currently have a CD Account with the bank, and are possibly from a county with a higher acceptance rate for personal loans such as Sonoma or Shasta county.
  • It will be interesting to see if any of these facotrs turn out to be the ones influencing personal loans and how close these demographic perdictions might be once we get results from our model.

Model Building¶

In [56]:
#function to check metrics

def model_perf_class_sklearn_threshold(model, predictors, target, threshold=0.5):
    """
    Function to calculate metrics, based on specified threshold, and check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    threshold: threshold for classifying the observation as class 1
    """

    # predict with independent variables
    pred_prob = model.predict_proba(predictors)[:, 1]
    pred_thresh = pred_prob > threshold
    pred = np.round(pred_thresh)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)                 

    # create a df for metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
          'Accuracy': acc,
          'Recall': recall,
          'Precision': precision,
          'F1': f1
        },
        index=[0]
    )

    return df_perf
In [57]:
#function for confusion_matrix
def confusion_matrix_sklearn_threshold(model, predictors, target, threshold=0.5):
    """
    Plot confusion_matrix, based on specified threshold, with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    threshold: threshold for classifying observation as class 1
    """
    pred_prob = model.predict_proba(predictors)[:, 1]
    pred_thresh = pred_prob > threshold
    y_pred = np.round(pred_thresh)

    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ['{0:0.0f}'.format(item) + '\n{0:.2%}'.format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt='')
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

Odds Observations¶

Some of the more notable odds are:

  • Family: Holding all other features constant a unit change in Family will increase the odds of a customer accepting a personal loan by 2.02 times or a 101.60% increase in the odds.
  • Education: Holding all other features constant a unit change in Education will increase the odds of a customer being accepting a personal loan by 4.77 times or a 377.50% increase in the odds.
  • CD_Account: Holding all other features constant having a CD_Account will increase the odds of a customer accepting a personal loan by 22.32 times or a 2132.13% increase in the odds.
  • Riverside and Solano counties both show over a 100% increase in odds
  • As far as negative change in odds 64.15% is the largest amount for a decrease in odds and this is with the coefficient for San Mateo County.
  • The negative changes have much lower changes in odd % comparitvely when looking at the positive changes in odd %

Improving Model Performance¶

Optimal threshold using AUC-ROC curve¶

  • I'm going to try and increase Recall, by changing the threshold using AUC-ROC Curve.
In [145]:
# For optimal threshold we want an AUC-ROC curve with high tpr and low fpr
fpr, tpr, thresh = roc_curve(y_train, lg.predict_proba(X_train)[:, 1])

optimal_idx = np.argmax(tpr - fpr)
optimal_thresh_auc_roc = thresholds[optimal_idx]

def plot_prec_recall_vs_tresh(precisions, recalls, thresholds):
    plt.plot(thresholds, precisions[:-1], 'b--', label='precision')
    plt.plot(thresholds, recalls[:-1], '--g', label='recall')
    plt.xlabel('Threshold')
    plt.legend(loc='upper left')
    plt.ylim([0, 1])

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
plot_prec_recall_vs_tresh(prec, rec, tre)
plt.show()
  • At threshold around 0.32 - 0.34 we will get equal precision and recall but I want a higher recall while keeping a good precision, so I think I'll go with 0.30

Conclusion¶

  • Changing the threshold for our logistic regression model made a significant improvement in the model performance.
  • The model achieved a recall of 0.91 on the training set with threshold set at 0.079, but the precision and f1 score suffered.
  • The best model for all metrics was the final model, when set at 0.30 for the threshold. This saw a 0.94 accuracy, a recall of 0.71, and a precision and f1 score of about 0.70 for each. Making the threshold of 0.30 the best overall performance.
  • The results of the 0.30 threshold performed even better on the test set by retaining the accuracy of 0.94, while giving us a recall of 0.75, with a precision of 0.71, and 0.73 for the f1 score.

Model evaluation criterion¶

Model can make wrong predictions as:¶

  1. Predicting that a customer will not purchase a personal loan but in reality the customer would purchase a personal loan.

  2. Predicting a customer will purchase a personal loan but in reality the customer would not purchase a personal loan.

Which case is more important?¶

  • If we predict that the correct customer deomographics for customers who would purchase a loan are in fact incorrect by saying they pertain to someone who would not be interested in purchasing a loan, then AllLife Bank would lose the opportunity of providing loans to potential customers.

How to reduce this loss i.e need to reduce False Negatives?¶

  • recall should be maximized, the greater the recall the greater the chances of minimizing the false negatives.
In [87]:
# function to compute metrics 
def model_perf_class_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to find metrics for checking performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    # predict independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)

    # create df for metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {'Accuracy': acc, 'Recall': recall, 'Precision': precision, 'F1': f1}, 
        index=[0]
    )

    return df_perf
In [88]:
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Confusion matrix with percents

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ['{0:0.0f}'.format(item) + '\n{0:.2%}'.format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt='')
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

Using GridSearch for Hyperparameter tuning of our tree model¶

  • Let's use GridSearch to improve our model further by tuning it
In [98]:
# Choose the type of classifier.
estimator = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1)

# Grid of parameters to choose from

parameters = {
      'max_depth': [2, 20, 5, None],
      'criterion': ['entropy', 'gini'],
      'splitter': ['best', 'random'],
      'min_impurity_decrease': [0.000001, 0.00001, 0.0001]
}

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
acc_scorer = make_scorer(recall_score)

# Run the grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(estimator, parameters, scoring=acc_scorer, cv=5)
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Set the clf to the best combination of parameters
estimator = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data.
estimator.fit(X_train, y_train)

Now we can train a tree using effective alphas. The last value in ccp_alphas is the value that prunes the whole tree, leaving the tree, clfs[-1], with one node.

In [107]:
clfs = []
for ccp_alpha in ccp_alphas:
    clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1, ccp_alpha=ccp_alpha)
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    clfs.append(clf)
print(
    'Number of nodes in the last tree is: {} with ccp_alpha: {}'.format(
        clfs[-1].tree_.node_count, ccp_alphas[-1]
    )
)

Number of nodes in the last tree is: 1 with ccp_alpha: 0.056364969335601575

Now we can remove the last element in clfs and ccp_alphas, because it has only one node. Number of nodes and tree depth should decreases as alpha increases.

In [108]:
clfs = clfs[:-1]
ccp_alphas = ccp_alphas[:-1]

node_counts = [clf.tree_.node_count for clf in clfs]
depth = [clf.tree_.max_depth for clf in clfs]
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(10,7))
ax[0].plot(ccp_alphas, node_counts, marker='o', drawstyle='steps-post')
ax[0].set_xlabel('alpha')
ax[0].set_ylabel('number of nodes')
ax[0].set_title('number of nodes vs alpha')
ax[1].plot(ccp_alphas, depth, marker='o', drawstyle='steps-post')

Business Insights¶

  • I would tell AllLife Bank's marketing department that Education, Income, and family are the metrics that they really want to focus on when creating their targeted marketing campaign. These are the most important features in determining whether or not a customer will purchase a personal loan.
  • For Education, we saw earlier in the EDA that category 3 - Advanced/Professional level of education had the highest number of customers who accepted a personal loan at 205 out of 1501 customers, giving an acceptance rate of 14%. Category 2 - Graduate level education was a very close 2nd with 182 out of 1403 customers purchasing a personal loan, for an acceptance rate of 13%. Then category 1 - undergrad education level had 93 out of 2096 which is an acceptance rate of 4%.
  • Based on these results, and Education being the most important feature, I would strongly reccomend focusing on targeted marketing aimed at customers who have an Advanced/Professional Education level and those that have a Graduate level education. Customers at these education levels will have the highest chances of purchasing a personal loan. There is a lot of untapped potential in this market as 58%, over half of your customers, fall within these two education levels.
  • Income is 2nd most important feature. With Income though, there is a larger spread of the data across many different individual income levels. One of the biggest things I could see from the EDA was that no cutomers making under 60,000 purchased a loan. This lines up well with Education level as those with higher levels of Education tend to have higher Incomes.
  • Looking at the top Income levels from the Bivariate Analysis, customers with 130,000 and 182,000 were the top categories with 11 customers at each income level accepting a personal loan. Then 158,000 and 135,000 were the next 2 income levels with 10 customers each. So you can see just from these top income levels, for personal loan purchases, that the values vary on a wide range of incomes.
  • I would highly reccomend taking the Income feature and segmenting it by larger income groups in order to get a more readable picture. Something such as < 60k, 60k > 120k, 120k > 180k, and so on. This would help to see what income ranges have the highest personal loan purchases instead of just focusing on above 60k and then some individualized income levels from the EDA.
  • Family was the 3rd major feature impacting a customers likelihood to purchase a personal loan. Looking at the EDA, 3 and 4 person families had the highest number of customers purchasing personal loans.
  • The 4 person family category had 134 customers out of 1,222 purchase personal loans, for an acceptance rate of 11%. 3 person families had 133 customers purchase a loan, only 1 less than 4 person families, but for 3 person families the acceptance rate was higher at 13%.
  • There was also just a single person difference between 1 and 2 person families, with individuals haveing purchased 107 personal loans for an acceptance rate of 7%. 2 person families had 106 customers purchase a personal loan for an acceptance rate of 8%.

Target Consumer:¶

  • Taking all of this information into account, I would reccomend that AllLife Bank's marketing department look at all the customers who have a 3 or 4 person Family, who also have a Graduate or an Advanced/Professional level of education, and make over 60,000 per year. The customers who fit all of these criteria are going to be the customers most likely to purchase a personal loan, based on the data.

    Equivalent to: [--TemplateExporter.exclude_output_prompt=True --TemplateExporter.exclude_input=True]

    Choices: any of [0, 10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 'DEBUG', 'INFO', 'WARN', 'ERROR', 'CRITICAL']
    Default: 30

    Default: ''

    Default: 'html'
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.export_format]

--reveal-prefix=<Unicode>
    The URL prefix for reveal.js (version 3.x).
            This defaults to the reveal CDN, but can be any url pointing to a copy

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb

            which will convert mynotebook.ipynb to the default format (probably HTML).

            You can specify the export format with `--to`.
            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'rst', 'script', 'slides'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic' and 'full'. You
            can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template basic mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of 
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.
